18
00:01:11,406 --> 00:01:14,007
that it shall
include in the call

19
00:01:14,042 --> 00:01:16,543
for the 1972 convention

20
00:01:16,577 --> 00:01:20,179
<i>the following addition
to section one...</i>

21
00:01:20,213 --> 00:01:24,150
<i>quote, it is the further
understanding...</i>

22
00:01:24,184 --> 00:01:27,787
<i>Should I pack your swim trunks?</i>

23
00:01:27,822 --> 00:01:30,423
What?

24
00:01:35,194 --> 00:01:37,228
They're supposed
to be debating the war.

25
00:01:37,263 --> 00:01:39,965
They can debate it all they want,
they just can't come out against it.

26
00:01:39,999 --> 00:01:42,133
Then no one will vote
for Humphrey.

27
00:01:42,168 --> 00:01:44,402
Over Nixon?

28
00:01:44,437 --> 00:01:47,806
Well, they can't have the whole
convention without talking about the war.

29
00:01:47,841 --> 00:01:51,242
30 seconds after prime time,
they'll start the debate.

30
00:01:52,445 --> 00:01:54,512
Cops have been hassling
protesters all day.

31
00:01:54,546 --> 00:01:58,116
Also not in prime time.

32
00:01:58,150 --> 00:01:59,517
You're so cynical.

33
00:01:59,551 --> 00:02:00,952
Come over here.

34
00:02:06,724 --> 00:02:08,525
Come with me.

35
00:02:08,559 --> 00:02:10,094
We'll go back to Disneyland.

36
00:02:10,128 --> 00:02:12,329
From what I remember, something
amazing happened there.

37
00:02:12,364 --> 00:02:15,632
- I made the biggest mistake of my life.
- That's true.

38
00:02:18,336 --> 00:02:20,036
You know I'd come if I could.

39
00:02:20,070 --> 00:02:21,871
You'll have fun.

40
00:02:21,905 --> 00:02:24,474
Just stay away from actresses.

41
00:02:24,508 --> 00:02:26,442
Do they have them out there?

42
00:02:26,477 --> 00:02:28,644
I hate actresses.

43
00:02:33,950 --> 00:02:35,784
Kenny said that this time
he went to a floor

44
00:02:35,819 --> 00:02:37,352
in the Chevy building
he'd never been to before.

45
00:02:37,387 --> 00:02:39,054
He said it was
like "Get Smart."

46
00:02:39,088 --> 00:02:40,922
Just a bunch of doors
in procession.

47
00:02:40,956 --> 00:02:43,825
And he met the man he believes to be
the source of our current torture.

48
00:02:43,859 --> 00:02:46,528
- What's his name? - Same as the
rest of them... Jack something.

49
00:02:46,562 --> 00:02:48,730
Apparently
his feelings were hurt

50
00:02:48,764 --> 00:02:50,399
because we haven't
kissed his ring.

51
00:02:50,433 --> 00:02:52,599
Well, I'd be happy to go
there and help soften him up.

52
00:02:52,634 --> 00:02:54,868
- If anyone's going, I'm going.
- But you can't

53
00:02:54,903 --> 00:02:57,138
because you're going to Los Angeles for...
what again?

54
00:02:57,172 --> 00:02:59,573
I'm going to pay them
a visit immediately.

55
00:02:59,607 --> 00:03:02,009
We don't want to miss our flight.
Are we going?

56
00:03:02,044 --> 00:03:03,544
Right after
the partners' meeting.

57
00:03:03,578 --> 00:03:05,712
Oh.

58
00:03:09,050 --> 00:03:10,683
Are we done here?

59
00:03:10,717 --> 00:03:13,253
Sweetheart, could you step out?

60
00:03:15,756 --> 00:03:17,723
This morning I received
an envelope addressed to

61
00:03:17,758 --> 00:03:19,825
Sterling Gleason and Pryce.

62
00:03:19,860 --> 00:03:22,095
- From who?
- It doesn't matter.

63
00:03:22,129 --> 00:03:24,863
They don't know our name because
we don't know our name.

64
00:03:24,897 --> 00:03:27,132
Aren't we SCDPCGC?

65
00:03:27,167 --> 00:03:28,567
Not officially.

66
00:03:28,601 --> 00:03:30,635
Well, I'm tired
of the conversation

67
00:03:30,670 --> 00:03:32,404
that goes along
with my business card.

68
00:03:32,439 --> 00:03:35,441
I know that no one has observed the
memo that requested specifically

69
00:03:35,475 --> 00:03:37,742
that all seven letters be used
when answering the phone.

70
00:03:37,777 --> 00:03:41,613
Sterling Cooper Draper Pryce Cutler
Gleason and Chaough? It's a mouthful.

71
00:03:41,647 --> 00:03:44,382
<i>SCDPCGC is a mouthful.</i>

72
00:03:44,416 --> 00:03:47,686
<i>But CGCSCDP is not.</i>

73
00:03:47,720 --> 00:03:50,354
- I don't agree.
- We've each lost a partner.

74
00:03:50,389 --> 00:03:52,057
Why don't we each
lose a letter?

75
00:03:52,091 --> 00:03:53,858
SCDC.

76
00:03:53,893 --> 00:03:56,527
- What do the Cs stand for?
- Not Campbell.

77
00:03:56,562 --> 00:03:57,895
Cooper and Cutler.

78
00:03:57,929 --> 00:03:59,396
Pardon me?

79
00:03:59,430 --> 00:04:03,000
Well, SCDCC sounds like a
stutter and looks like a typo.

80
00:04:04,302 --> 00:04:06,336
Very well, if it puts
this to rest,

81
00:04:06,370 --> 00:04:08,338
I will gladly withdraw my name

82
00:04:08,372 --> 00:04:12,109
along with the other deceased
parties in this conversation.

83
00:04:12,143 --> 00:04:13,943
Bert, don't be a martyr.

84
00:04:13,978 --> 00:04:16,345
Want to throw away
both of these brands?

85
00:04:16,379 --> 00:04:18,447
Just leave it alone. We'll
get a bigger front door.

86
00:04:18,482 --> 00:04:20,883
Well, of course you like it.
You're at the front.

87
00:04:20,918 --> 00:04:22,819
<i>- I'm at the end.
- I'm at the end.</i>

88
00:04:22,853 --> 00:04:24,520
Well, I move to table this.

89
00:04:24,554 --> 00:04:26,089
You have fun in Detroit.

90
00:04:26,123 --> 00:04:27,724
And you have fun
with Manischewitz.

91
00:04:27,758 --> 00:04:29,091
Any special instructions?

92
00:04:29,125 --> 00:04:32,527
Yeah, the guy in charge, just
pick an eye and stick with it.

93
00:04:32,561 --> 00:04:34,997
Very well, but it's my belief
that any further delay

94
00:04:35,031 --> 00:04:37,132
in choosing our name
will take it out of our hands

95
00:04:37,166 --> 00:04:39,334
and leave it up to the world.

96
00:04:48,877 --> 00:04:51,445
You know Sunkist is still
only doing print work?

97
00:04:51,479 --> 00:04:54,181
I'm cutting you off.

98
00:04:54,215 --> 00:04:57,217
- You're two ahead of me.
- No, from work.

99
00:04:57,252 --> 00:04:59,453
Come on.
We're executives.

100
00:04:59,487 --> 00:05:01,154
Leave the drudgery
to Ted Chaough

101
00:05:01,188 --> 00:05:02,488
and the rest of the underlings.

102
00:05:02,523 --> 00:05:03,723
Did you prepare at all?

103
00:05:03,758 --> 00:05:07,193
Sunkist, Carnation,
the avocado people.

104
00:05:07,227 --> 00:05:09,129
My biggest job
in these meetings

105
00:05:09,163 --> 00:05:11,865
is to keep them from saying
"golly" too many times.

106
00:05:11,899 --> 00:05:14,233
Carnation has 27 million
in billings.

107
00:05:14,268 --> 00:05:16,702
I don't think the guy in charge
ties his pants with a rope.

108
00:05:16,736 --> 00:05:19,337
I didn't say that. But I guarantee
they all have a certain regard

109
00:05:19,372 --> 00:05:20,873
for two gentlemen
from the big city.

110
00:05:20,907 --> 00:05:22,274
You mean they won't trust us?

111
00:05:22,308 --> 00:05:24,176
I mean they don't
trust themselves.

112
00:05:24,210 --> 00:05:25,577
I don't know if you realize it,

113
00:05:25,611 --> 00:05:27,612
but we are big New York admen

114
00:05:27,647 --> 00:05:29,982
from an agency with seven
letters in its name.

115
00:05:30,016 --> 00:05:32,051
That means under
no circumstances

116
00:05:32,085 --> 00:05:35,687
are you to trot out that drawl
you do when you've had too many.

117
00:05:35,721 --> 00:05:39,023
<i>Be slick. Be glib.
Be you.</i>

118
00:05:39,058 --> 00:05:41,759
Well, I'm usually informed.

119
00:05:41,794 --> 00:05:43,795
We're conquistadors.

120
00:05:43,829 --> 00:05:46,430
I'm Vasco da Gama and
you're some other Mexican.

121
00:05:46,464 --> 00:05:49,332
We're gonna land there, buy whatever
they've got for the beads in our pockets.

122
00:05:49,366 --> 00:05:52,803
Our biggest challenge
is to not get syphilis.

123
00:05:52,837 --> 00:05:54,871
Cathy.

124
00:05:54,906 --> 00:05:56,673
Another round.

125
00:05:56,708 --> 00:05:58,809
And send one to the pilot.

126
00:06:05,481 --> 00:06:07,316
<i>...hours of acrimonious debate,</i>

127
00:06:07,350 --> 00:06:09,919
<i>the Democratic National
Convention has rejected a plank</i>

128
00:06:09,953 --> 00:06:11,721
<i>advanced by Democratic doves</i>

129
00:06:11,755 --> 00:06:14,556
<i>calling for an unconditional
end to all bombing</i>

130
00:06:14,591 --> 00:06:16,625
<i>of North Vietnam.</i>

131
00:06:17,961 --> 00:06:19,494
What's going on?

132
00:06:19,529 --> 00:06:21,996
They delayed till noon
and then they rejected it.

133
00:06:22,031 --> 00:06:24,199
- Rejected what?
- The peace plank.

134
00:06:24,233 --> 00:06:26,701
Chance to have a platform
against the war.

135
00:06:26,736 --> 00:06:29,604
Uh-huh. Then let me
clarify my question.

136
00:06:29,638 --> 00:06:31,639
What's going on with
the work for Manischewitz?

137
00:06:31,673 --> 00:06:33,441
Because you're for the war.

138
00:06:33,475 --> 00:06:35,877
You know there's 200
body bags every week.

139
00:06:35,911 --> 00:06:37,611
Figure out how to get
into that business yet?

140
00:06:37,645 --> 00:06:39,880
I refuse to be distracted

141
00:06:39,914 --> 00:06:42,816
by events in which I have no
actual stake or participation.

142
00:06:42,851 --> 00:06:44,351
How could you say that?

143
00:06:44,385 --> 00:06:45,719
Because he doesn't
have any sons.

144
00:06:45,754 --> 00:06:48,055
I served in the Air Force.
Did you?

145
00:06:48,089 --> 00:06:50,457
You're disgusting,
you know that?

146
00:06:50,491 --> 00:06:53,459
This whole thing works because
people like you look the other way.

147
00:06:53,493 --> 00:06:56,028
- Ginsberg.
- My politics are private.

148
00:06:56,063 --> 00:06:57,563
But that presentation isn't.

149
00:06:57,597 --> 00:06:59,999
Now, are you gonna hide your
dawdling behind your outrage?

150
00:07:00,033 --> 00:07:01,768
You'll have your work
and you know it.

151
00:07:01,802 --> 00:07:04,771
You can go in there and take
credit for it like you always do.

152
00:07:04,805 --> 00:07:08,374
Be friendly and charming after you've
stuck your fascist boot on my neck.

153
00:07:08,408 --> 00:07:10,708
So I'm a fascist because
I gave you a deadline?

154
00:07:10,743 --> 00:07:13,044
No, you're a fascist
because you love business

155
00:07:13,079 --> 00:07:16,214
and you hate everything
else... freedom, blacks, Jews.

156
00:07:16,249 --> 00:07:17,849
This is my stop.

157
00:07:17,884 --> 00:07:19,450
I hate hypocrites.

158
00:07:19,485 --> 00:07:22,821
Like hippies who cash checks from
Dow Chemical and General Motors.

159
00:07:22,855 --> 00:07:25,756
You rooting for the Soviets
in Prague, too, you Nazi?

160
00:07:25,791 --> 00:07:28,458
Michael, what are you doing?
That man is your boss.

161
00:07:28,493 --> 00:07:31,561
Why are you always down here?
Go back upstairs!

162
00:07:32,664 --> 00:07:34,698
You're a truncheon, Cutler.

163
00:07:36,501 --> 00:07:38,836
Thanks for making that worse.

164
00:07:43,640 --> 00:07:45,875
Hello, Ted.

165
00:07:45,910 --> 00:07:47,877
- You busy?
- Extremely.

166
00:07:47,912 --> 00:07:51,347
I think you know
I'm a man without regrets,

167
00:07:51,381 --> 00:07:53,749
but I do believe
we fired the wrong people

168
00:07:53,784 --> 00:07:55,985
and I'd like to remedy
that immediately.

169
00:07:56,020 --> 00:07:58,954
Jim, I think you're upset.

170
00:07:58,988 --> 00:08:01,023
No, because I have a solution.

171
00:08:01,057 --> 00:08:02,977
I think we should remove
the rest of their people

172
00:08:02,992 --> 00:08:05,560
while Sterling, Draper,
and Crane are in California.

173
00:08:05,594 --> 00:08:09,064
Just lock the gates and leave
Pete Campbell as the doorman.

174
00:08:09,098 --> 00:08:11,566
- What happened?
- Do I need cause?

175
00:08:11,600 --> 00:08:13,535
How about failure
to complete tasks

176
00:08:13,569 --> 00:08:15,136
coupled with gross
insubordination?

177
00:08:15,170 --> 00:08:17,572
Maybe part of it is you
keep seeing this agency

178
00:08:17,606 --> 00:08:19,341
as our people and their people.

179
00:08:19,375 --> 00:08:22,009
Well, how about your people
and my people?

180
00:08:22,044 --> 00:08:24,178
Do I have permission
to clean out creative,

181
00:08:24,213 --> 00:08:25,747
starting with
Mr. Ginsberg?

182
00:08:25,781 --> 00:08:27,515
Jim, he's lightning
in a bottle.

183
00:08:27,550 --> 00:08:30,250
You have to start holding
hands, starting with his.

184
00:08:30,284 --> 00:08:31,918
Because I'll be in
Detroit tomorrow

185
00:08:31,953 --> 00:08:33,487
and you're taking him
to Manischewitz.

186
00:08:33,521 --> 00:08:36,156
Sterling's client
and Draper's boy.

187
00:08:39,193 --> 00:08:41,228
I'm the world's
most expensive babysitter.

188
00:08:41,262 --> 00:08:42,496
That's the spirit.

189
00:08:45,966 --> 00:08:48,835
I suppose I wouldn't be a
good friend if I didn't ask...

190
00:08:48,869 --> 00:08:50,430
is Kate pulling
her weight around there?

191
00:08:50,437 --> 00:08:52,739
She arranged this.

192
00:08:52,773 --> 00:08:54,707
She did.

193
00:08:56,176 --> 00:08:59,645
Well, Kate told me that
you're the kind of woman

194
00:08:59,680 --> 00:09:01,781
who won't just tell me
what I want to hear.

195
00:09:01,815 --> 00:09:03,782
I hope she didn't make
any promises.

196
00:09:05,385 --> 00:09:07,319
My wife always says
I'm the kind of man

197
00:09:07,354 --> 00:09:09,721
who doesn't like
to ask for directions.

198
00:09:09,756 --> 00:09:12,224
My new job has me
face-to-face with ad agencies.

199
00:09:12,259 --> 00:09:13,558
I don't know what I'm doing.

200
00:09:13,593 --> 00:09:16,695
Kate said you were divorced.

201
00:09:17,897 --> 00:09:19,663
I am.

202
00:09:19,698 --> 00:09:21,232
I forgot.

203
00:09:21,267 --> 00:09:23,734
What does that say?

204
00:09:25,604 --> 00:09:28,072
Anyway, what should
I look for in an agency?

205
00:09:29,808 --> 00:09:32,911
Oh, well, a good agency
should tell you.

206
00:09:32,945 --> 00:09:34,644
Go ahead.

207
00:09:34,678 --> 00:09:36,179
Me?

208
00:09:36,214 --> 00:09:37,647
That's why I'm here.

209
00:09:42,153 --> 00:09:44,121
Yes.

210
00:09:44,155 --> 00:09:46,256
Of course.

211
00:09:47,525 --> 00:09:51,327
Well, I suppose we don't
just lean on

212
00:09:51,361 --> 00:09:53,462
stylish creative,
or market research.

213
00:09:53,496 --> 00:09:55,531
We listen to the client.

214
00:09:55,565 --> 00:09:57,599
Doesn't everybody do that?

215
00:09:57,634 --> 00:10:00,369
Despite your modesty,
you already know

216
00:10:00,404 --> 00:10:02,571
that the way to get invited
into people's homes

217
00:10:02,605 --> 00:10:04,140
is through their TV sets.

218
00:10:04,174 --> 00:10:08,076
Media placement is part
science, part courage.

219
00:10:08,110 --> 00:10:11,012
Anyone can tell you not to run
makeup ads during football.

220
00:10:11,047 --> 00:10:14,082
The trick is finding
your customers

221
00:10:14,116 --> 00:10:15,850
in places you hadn't
thought to look.

222
00:10:15,884 --> 00:10:18,320
Harry Crane is a wizard.

223
00:10:18,354 --> 00:10:21,323
They use a computer
the size of this restaurant.

224
00:10:21,357 --> 00:10:23,057
And what is your job there?

225
00:10:24,759 --> 00:10:27,027
I'm in charge
of thinking of things

226
00:10:27,062 --> 00:10:28,862
before people
know they need them.

227
00:10:35,235 --> 00:10:37,770
- I've got this.
- Come on.

228
00:10:37,804 --> 00:10:40,673
Please, this is what
I get paid to do.

229
00:10:51,550 --> 00:10:53,852
I was just coming to see you.

230
00:10:55,254 --> 00:10:56,588
But you're not going anywhere.

231
00:10:56,622 --> 00:10:59,291
I was, but then you appeared.

232
00:10:59,325 --> 00:11:02,326
At the risk of playing defense,

233
00:11:02,361 --> 00:11:05,863
I only interfered
because I hate disrespect.

234
00:11:05,897 --> 00:11:08,966
I don't know
what you're talking about.

235
00:11:10,168 --> 00:11:12,336
- Neither do I.
- Hmm.

236
00:11:12,371 --> 00:11:15,272
I believe in you, Bob.
But you're untested.

237
00:11:15,307 --> 00:11:17,574
Manischewitz,
tomorrow afternoon...

238
00:11:17,609 --> 00:11:19,309
think you can handle
the parties involved?

239
00:11:19,343 --> 00:11:22,678
Michael Ginsberg
or the clients?

240
00:11:22,713 --> 00:11:24,680
I don't see much
difference, do you?

241
00:11:24,715 --> 00:11:27,783
I think I can
keep the volume down.

242
00:11:27,818 --> 00:11:29,752
Excellent.

243
00:11:29,786 --> 00:11:32,022
I welcome this chance to shine.

244
00:11:49,506 --> 00:11:52,573
- Are you on a deadline?
- No, do you need me?

245
00:11:52,607 --> 00:11:54,008
I need a drink.

246
00:11:54,043 --> 00:11:55,609
Okay.

247
00:11:55,644 --> 00:11:57,645
I had this lunch
my friend Kate set up

248
00:11:57,679 --> 00:12:00,048
and I think
it's a potential client.

249
00:12:00,082 --> 00:12:01,949
- I know he is.
- Who is he?

250
00:12:01,983 --> 00:12:03,918
The new head
of marketing at Avon.

251
00:12:05,854 --> 00:12:08,055
I thought it was a date, but
it turned out to be better.

252
00:12:08,089 --> 00:12:09,990
- I love Avon.
- Of course.

253
00:12:10,025 --> 00:12:11,659
And you'd be perfect for it.

254
00:12:11,693 --> 00:12:14,494
It's just... I don't know
what to do with it.

255
00:12:14,529 --> 00:12:16,329
He's leaving town tomorrow.

256
00:12:16,364 --> 00:12:18,098
So set a meeting.

257
00:12:18,132 --> 00:12:19,900
I know I have to,
but Don's not here

258
00:12:19,935 --> 00:12:21,669
and I don't want to get
kicked off the diving board.

259
00:12:21,703 --> 00:12:23,870
We'll take it to Ted.

260
00:12:23,904 --> 00:12:26,238
- He'll know what to do.
- What did I just say?

261
00:12:26,273 --> 00:12:27,907
He's not like that.

262
00:12:29,242 --> 00:12:30,610
And what do I ask for?

263
00:12:30,644 --> 00:12:32,278
I don't know.

264
00:12:32,312 --> 00:12:34,781
You'll be the account man
if that's what you want.

265
00:12:36,316 --> 00:12:38,217
Trust me,
he loves new business.

266
00:12:38,251 --> 00:12:40,919
He doesn't care where it comes from.
Let's go.

267
00:12:45,291 --> 00:12:48,159
- I told you I wanted a rental car.
- They insisted.

268
00:12:48,194 --> 00:12:50,295
- Ted, do you have a minute?
- Just barely.

269
00:12:50,329 --> 00:12:53,131
Well, it's kind of urgent.
Joan has a solid lead.

270
00:12:53,165 --> 00:12:54,899
He's leaving tomorrow.
We need to set a meeting.

271
00:12:54,933 --> 00:12:56,934
Good for you. Get Pete
Campbell down here.

272
00:12:56,969 --> 00:12:59,870
- Who is it?
- It's Avon Cosmetics.

273
00:12:59,905 --> 00:13:01,706
<i>- It's Moira. Can you send him down
immediately? - Very groovy.</i>

274
00:13:01,740 --> 00:13:05,009
The new head of marketing, he's a
friend of a very close friend of mine

275
00:13:05,043 --> 00:13:06,677
and I just wanted
to introduce him to Peggy.

276
00:13:06,712 --> 00:13:08,846
- Peggy'd be perfect for it.
- You rang?

277
00:13:08,880 --> 00:13:10,247
Pete, as head
of new business...

278
00:13:10,281 --> 00:13:11,982
Since when?
I don't want that.

279
00:13:12,016 --> 00:13:13,717
Joan has a lead
for Avon Cosmetics.

280
00:13:13,751 --> 00:13:16,519
Peggy's creative. He's leaving
town tomorrow. Reel him in.

281
00:13:16,553 --> 00:13:19,489
<i>Fly safe.</i>

282
00:13:19,523 --> 00:13:21,290
Avon Cosmetics.

283
00:13:21,325 --> 00:13:23,493
That's Fortune 500.
What's his name?

284
00:13:23,527 --> 00:13:25,495
Andy Hayes.

285
00:13:25,529 --> 00:13:29,064
My friend Kate just moved there from
Mary Kay and she sent him my way.

286
00:13:29,099 --> 00:13:32,334
Tell me everything you can about him and
set lunch tomorrow for Peggy and me.

287
00:13:32,368 --> 00:13:34,269
I should be there.

288
00:13:34,303 --> 00:13:36,739
Joan, this is how
things get botched.

289
00:13:36,773 --> 00:13:38,573
First, account man
and creative.

290
00:13:38,608 --> 00:13:40,342
Then if all goes well,
next trip

291
00:13:40,376 --> 00:13:42,577
he visits the office
and you show him around.

292
00:13:42,612 --> 00:13:45,046
I think he'll be expecting me.

293
00:13:45,080 --> 00:13:46,748
Shouldn't Joan
make the introductions?

294
00:13:46,782 --> 00:13:48,582
I don't understand
what the problem is.

295
00:13:48,617 --> 00:13:50,618
You're going to make the call

296
00:13:50,653 --> 00:13:53,487
and tell him how important I
am and how exciting Peggy is.

297
00:13:53,522 --> 00:13:56,157
And then we're going to tell
him how essential you are.

298
00:13:57,693 --> 00:13:59,926
Don't worry.
You'll get all the credit.

299
00:14:01,595 --> 00:14:03,664
Clara.
Are you coming?

300
00:14:37,462 --> 00:14:39,898
Hey, I let you sit up front.

301
00:14:39,932 --> 00:14:42,433
Sorry about that.
You need a hand?

302
00:14:42,467 --> 00:14:43,802
What?

303
00:14:46,771 --> 00:14:48,939
There's no one
from GM in Los Angeles?

304
00:14:48,973 --> 00:14:50,507
Get rid of that car.

305
00:14:50,541 --> 00:14:52,109
And get us something
with a roof.

306
00:14:52,143 --> 00:14:54,511
Don't want to show up to a
meeting with bugs in my teeth.

307
00:14:54,545 --> 00:14:56,646
So, you want to take
a dip in the pool

308
00:14:56,681 --> 00:14:58,281
or should I
just wait in the bar?

309
00:14:58,316 --> 00:15:00,483
- Both have attractive scenery.
- Where's the bellman?

310
00:15:00,518 --> 00:15:03,186
Mañana, Don.
Everything's mañana here.

311
00:15:03,220 --> 00:15:05,922
I'm gonna take a shower. You can
wait in the bar if you want.

312
00:15:05,956 --> 00:15:07,724
I'm gonna get room service.

313
00:15:07,758 --> 00:15:09,258
We're gonna go
to the Sunset Strip,

314
00:15:09,292 --> 00:15:10,760
watch a girl dance in a cage.

315
00:15:10,794 --> 00:15:12,261
That you heard?

316
00:15:12,295 --> 00:15:13,535
Save your strength
for tomorrow.

317
00:15:13,563 --> 00:15:15,631
Going to a party in the hills.

318
00:15:15,665 --> 00:15:17,466
- It's very hip.
- Beverly Hills?

319
00:15:17,500 --> 00:15:20,468
<i>No, the hills. And
it's movies, not TV.</i>

320
00:15:20,502 --> 00:15:23,504
My friend in development at CBS says
it's going to be crawling with moguls.

321
00:15:23,539 --> 00:15:25,373
- Jesus, it's hot here.
- It's a dry heat.

322
00:15:25,407 --> 00:15:27,209
It's a dry heave.

323
00:15:27,243 --> 00:15:29,510
Come on, Don, let's go to the Strip
right now and get some dinner.

324
00:15:29,545 --> 00:15:31,079
No, I'm gonna turn in.

325
00:15:31,114 --> 00:15:33,882
Tried to sleep on the plane, but
somebody wouldn't stop talking.

326
00:15:37,285 --> 00:15:39,419
Don't worry, I got this.

327
00:15:42,893 --> 00:15:44,761
<i>This is on tape since again
we're not able to cover it live.</i>

328
00:15:44,795 --> 00:15:46,462
The tape you're about
to see was made

329
00:15:46,497 --> 00:15:49,164
about 30 to 40 minutes ago.

330
00:16:33,641 --> 00:16:37,275
<i>It was supposed to be a
nonviolent demonstration today.</i>

331
00:16:40,079 --> 00:16:42,948
<i>And one will never know
what it was</i>

332
00:16:42,982 --> 00:16:45,183
<i>that made it become violent.</i>

333
00:16:47,520 --> 00:16:49,621
<i>This is directly
in front of what advertises itself</i>

334
00:16:49,656 --> 00:16:52,022
<i>as the world's largest
and friendliest hotel.</i>

335
00:16:52,057 --> 00:16:54,692
<i>Where at this hour
people stand around</i>

336
00:16:54,726 --> 00:16:56,226
<i>and sit in their rooms
with handkerchiefs...</i>

337
00:16:56,261 --> 00:16:59,196
- Hello.
- Are you watching this?

338
00:16:59,230 --> 00:17:01,499
Yeah.

339
00:17:01,533 --> 00:17:03,167
It's hard to believe
no one got killed.

340
00:17:03,201 --> 00:17:06,170
That the only measure?

341
00:17:06,204 --> 00:17:08,605
Can you imagine a policeman
cracking your skull?

342
00:17:08,639 --> 00:17:10,207
It would change
your whole life.

343
00:17:10,241 --> 00:17:12,209
Honey, they're throwing rocks.

344
00:17:12,243 --> 00:17:13,810
They're prepared for trouble.

345
00:17:19,017 --> 00:17:21,285
<i>In some places, plainclothesmen</i>

346
00:17:21,319 --> 00:17:22,853
<i>are helping make the arrests.</i>

347
00:17:26,556 --> 00:17:30,226
On the bright side, Conrad Hilton is
probably in that hotel right now.

348
00:17:30,260 --> 00:17:32,161
Don't make jokes.

349
00:17:32,196 --> 00:17:34,063
Megan, you can't even vote.

350
00:17:35,265 --> 00:17:37,133
But I live here.

351
00:17:38,902 --> 00:17:40,636
I'm sorry.

352
00:17:45,775 --> 00:17:48,811
I want you to be careful.

353
00:17:48,845 --> 00:17:50,479
This could easily start a riot.

354
00:17:50,514 --> 00:17:52,781
Don't worry.
I'm not going anywhere.

355
00:17:52,816 --> 00:17:54,750
Really?

356
00:17:54,784 --> 00:17:56,985
You can if you want to.

357
00:17:57,019 --> 00:17:59,587
I miss you.

358
00:18:01,223 --> 00:18:03,391
Go for a swim.

359
00:18:03,425 --> 00:18:05,359
It always makes you
feel better.

360
00:18:05,394 --> 00:18:08,496
<i>The whole world is watching.</i>

361
00:18:11,500 --> 00:18:14,601
The whole world is watching.
The whole world is watching.

362
00:18:14,636 --> 00:18:16,737
<i>There's a break
in the arrests now...</i>

363
00:18:16,771 --> 00:18:19,439
We should hang up.
This is costing a fortune.

364
00:18:19,473 --> 00:18:21,575
Try and get some sleep.

365
00:18:21,609 --> 00:18:23,644
You, too.

366
00:18:23,678 --> 00:18:26,112
Bye.

367
00:18:28,016 --> 00:18:30,182
Bye.

368
00:18:49,035 --> 00:18:51,836
So you came after all.

369
00:18:51,871 --> 00:18:53,738
Pete couldn't make it.

370
00:18:53,773 --> 00:18:56,608
What? How the hell are
we supposed to do this?

371
00:18:56,642 --> 00:18:58,877
Don't worry about it.
Coffee, please.

372
00:19:00,512 --> 00:19:02,880
I didn't know Ted was going
to handle it that way.

373
00:19:02,914 --> 00:19:04,848
Well, he did.

374
00:19:04,883 --> 00:19:08,686
And Pete's not coming...

375
00:19:08,720 --> 00:19:10,054
because he wasn't invited.

376
00:19:11,990 --> 00:19:14,625
- You can't do that.
- I did it.

377
00:19:14,659 --> 00:19:16,460
If you want to leave, go ahead.

378
00:19:16,494 --> 00:19:19,929
I hope I didn't keep you waiting,
but I was trying to check out.

379
00:19:19,964 --> 00:19:22,125
See, if you were a client,
you could have left your key

380
00:19:22,132 --> 00:19:24,667
at the desk and we would
have attended to that.

381
00:19:24,702 --> 00:19:26,703
Andy Hayes, Peggy Olson.

382
00:19:26,737 --> 00:19:28,671
She's the dynamite
in our creative department.

383
00:19:28,706 --> 00:19:30,139
I don't know about that.

384
00:19:30,173 --> 00:19:31,808
Tomato juice
and coffee, please.

385
00:19:33,409 --> 00:19:35,978
I didn't want you to leave New
York without meeting Peggy.

386
00:19:36,012 --> 00:19:39,081
Her expertise has been honed
by her work on Clearasil,

387
00:19:39,115 --> 00:19:42,150
Pond's Cold Cream, and most
relevant, Belle Jolie lipsticks.

388
00:19:42,184 --> 00:19:43,885
I almost worked there.

389
00:19:43,920 --> 00:19:45,420
Do you remember
"Mark your man"?

390
00:19:45,454 --> 00:19:47,022
I do.

391
00:19:47,056 --> 00:19:49,356
I grew up in an Avon home.

392
00:19:49,390 --> 00:19:51,959
Our lady was Gladys Bowman.

393
00:19:51,994 --> 00:19:53,694
She was very elegant.

394
00:19:53,729 --> 00:19:57,031
My mother would vacuum
the drapes before she came.

395
00:19:57,065 --> 00:19:59,500
Then my sister and I would
fight over the catalogue.

396
00:19:59,534 --> 00:20:02,202
- In fact...
- In fact, all women

397
00:20:02,237 --> 00:20:05,238
have some kind of personal
connection to Avon.

398
00:20:05,272 --> 00:20:07,674
But that doesn't turn into
advertising, now, does it?

399
00:20:07,708 --> 00:20:10,510
Why don't you tell us
your biggest challenge?

400
00:20:10,544 --> 00:20:13,980
We're here to listen. It's just
hard to hide our enthusiasm.

401
00:20:14,015 --> 00:20:16,215
It's true.

402
00:20:16,250 --> 00:20:18,118
Well, they don't
bring in a new guy

403
00:20:18,152 --> 00:20:21,053
unless they're expanding
or sales are flat.

404
00:20:21,087 --> 00:20:23,689
I'm afraid it's the latter.

405
00:20:23,723 --> 00:20:26,324
Women are working.
They're not home.

406
00:20:26,359 --> 00:20:29,161
And hippies don't wear
makeup at all.

407
00:20:29,195 --> 00:20:31,363
I'm not sure if we should
try to be "groovier"

408
00:20:31,397 --> 00:20:33,398
or nostalgic.

409
00:20:33,432 --> 00:20:35,600
We're somewhere
in between right now.

410
00:20:38,003 --> 00:20:39,871
That's about it.

411
00:20:42,207 --> 00:20:43,474
Peggy?

412
00:20:43,508 --> 00:20:45,677
Yes, Joan?

413
00:20:49,214 --> 00:20:51,549
What do you think
of your current work?

414
00:20:51,583 --> 00:20:53,249
Besides the fact
that it's not working?

415
00:20:55,219 --> 00:20:57,220
It's okay.
We didn't do it.

416
00:20:57,254 --> 00:20:59,222
I don't know how
to describe it.

417
00:20:59,256 --> 00:21:02,092
Would you say it's
unintentionally old-fashioned?

418
00:21:02,126 --> 00:21:04,027
Yes.

419
00:21:04,062 --> 00:21:05,395
Yes, I would.

420
00:21:06,564 --> 00:21:08,498
I'm sure you've thought
of this already,

421
00:21:08,532 --> 00:21:11,100
but Joan and I were saying
how convenient it would be

422
00:21:11,134 --> 00:21:14,403
to have the Avon lady come to
the office maybe during lunch.

423
00:21:14,437 --> 00:21:17,807
Well, they're not resistant to
trying that, just to advertising it.

424
00:21:17,841 --> 00:21:20,109
There's no doorbell
in an office.

425
00:21:25,981 --> 00:21:27,749
I only saw a little bit
of it on the morning news,

426
00:21:27,783 --> 00:21:31,086
but I'm sorry I missed
Humphrey's acceptance speech.

427
00:21:31,120 --> 00:21:32,821
I assume he was
high-voiced and desperate.

428
00:21:32,855 --> 00:21:35,576
You're the exception. Early numbers
look like over 80 million people.

429
00:21:35,591 --> 00:21:38,093
Look, we all hated what we saw,

430
00:21:38,127 --> 00:21:40,861
but the Democrats are dead.
It's over.

431
00:21:40,895 --> 00:21:43,897
Not just now, maybe forever.

432
00:21:46,167 --> 00:21:48,168
As you were.
Nobody get up.

433
00:21:48,203 --> 00:21:50,170
Nonsense, Jack.
Great to see you finally.

434
00:21:50,205 --> 00:21:52,005
Roger Sterling, Don Draper.

435
00:21:54,042 --> 00:21:57,409
George was just laughing that these
riots gave Nixon the election.

436
00:21:59,079 --> 00:22:01,013
I don't think that's
anything to smile about.

437
00:22:02,282 --> 00:22:04,316
And although this boardroom
has been the site

438
00:22:04,351 --> 00:22:06,753
of many casual
political conversations

439
00:22:06,787 --> 00:22:08,587
among better men than us,

440
00:22:08,622 --> 00:22:10,223
this is a business meeting.

441
00:22:10,257 --> 00:22:12,424
You're right, Jack.

442
00:22:13,692 --> 00:22:15,460
Last night was disgusting,

443
00:22:15,494 --> 00:22:19,965
<i>seeing those long-haired
fools shame this country.</i>

444
00:22:19,999 --> 00:22:23,068
You think Richard Nixon
is going to fix that?

445
00:22:23,102 --> 00:22:25,603
I think he's a patriot.

446
00:22:25,638 --> 00:22:27,538
Dutch Reagan is a patriot.

447
00:22:27,573 --> 00:22:29,406
Nixon is an opportunist.

448
00:22:31,877 --> 00:22:34,979
Now why don't you gentlemen
tell us how it's possible

449
00:22:35,013 --> 00:22:37,047
to devote your energies
to our nutritious

450
00:22:37,082 --> 00:22:39,049
and delicious Instant Breakfast

451
00:22:39,084 --> 00:22:41,385
and Life Cereal
at the same time?

452
00:22:42,921 --> 00:22:45,088
Well, Jack,

453
00:22:45,122 --> 00:22:48,224
your powdered milk
and dairy products

454
00:22:48,259 --> 00:22:51,828
have had a long, successful
relationship with breakfast cereal.

455
00:22:51,862 --> 00:22:53,596
There's no reason
to give that up.

456
00:22:53,630 --> 00:22:55,531
And as far as we can tell,

457
00:22:55,565 --> 00:22:58,367
Instant Breakfast has
a different target... adults.

458
00:22:59,569 --> 00:23:01,069
They don't eat cereal.

459
00:23:01,104 --> 00:23:03,205
They eat bacon and eggs.

460
00:23:03,239 --> 00:23:05,340
And this is healthier,

461
00:23:05,374 --> 00:23:08,310
easier, and instant.

462
00:23:08,344 --> 00:23:11,746
And what if we were to say we
find the conflict unresolvable?

463
00:23:11,781 --> 00:23:14,283
I'm sorry to interrupt, but we
discussed this over the phone.

464
00:23:14,317 --> 00:23:17,952
This is about a whole different level
of exposure for your products.

465
00:23:17,986 --> 00:23:20,321
All of them. You should
be in game shows.

466
00:23:20,355 --> 00:23:21,889
You should have a presence
on Saturday morning.

467
00:23:21,924 --> 00:23:24,358
Where we'll sit right next
to one of your cereal ads?

468
00:23:25,861 --> 00:23:28,930
- Don?
- Look, Jack, George,

469
00:23:28,964 --> 00:23:32,966
I'm sure you know that we would
do anything to make this work.

470
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:35,135
We believe that strongly
in Carnation.

471
00:23:35,169 --> 00:23:36,703
We believe in the wholesomeness

472
00:23:36,737 --> 00:23:40,540
of both your intentions
and your products.

473
00:23:40,574 --> 00:23:42,475
To be frank,

474
00:23:42,509 --> 00:23:45,111
we've worked with
New York firms before.

475
00:23:45,146 --> 00:23:47,547
We come in in the
morning, try to get you,

476
00:23:47,581 --> 00:23:49,181
everyone's at lunch.

477
00:23:49,216 --> 00:23:51,250
And when people
are at lunch around here,

478
00:23:51,284 --> 00:23:53,986
that's just the time
we get a message from you.

479
00:23:54,020 --> 00:23:56,621
And with it comes an attitude

480
00:23:56,656 --> 00:23:59,158
as if to say we're not
working hard out here.

481
00:23:59,192 --> 00:24:02,394
I can assure you, it is
very much to the contrary.

482
00:24:02,428 --> 00:24:05,663
Look, we're sorry your
last girlfriend hurt you.

483
00:24:06,832 --> 00:24:08,566
We're in your office right now.

484
00:24:11,803 --> 00:24:13,404
Tell us what you have in mind.

485
00:24:21,111 --> 00:24:24,245
What is going on? I just handed
you the business of your life.

486
00:24:24,279 --> 00:24:26,414
What is going on?
You just threw it away.

487
00:24:26,448 --> 00:24:28,549
Morning, ladies.

488
00:24:28,584 --> 00:24:30,884
- Morning.
- Morning.

489
00:24:30,919 --> 00:24:32,886
Stop that.

490
00:24:32,921 --> 00:24:35,623
What exactly
are you planning to do?

491
00:24:35,657 --> 00:24:37,658
Are you trying
to intimidate me?

492
00:24:37,692 --> 00:24:40,494
No, that's always
been impossible

493
00:24:40,528 --> 00:24:42,562
because that would require
respect for me or what I do.

494
00:24:42,597 --> 00:24:46,399
I know you want this,
and now you can't have it.

495
00:24:46,434 --> 00:24:48,268
You could've,
